issue.title: Your Pricing Is a Wallet-Wrecking Tragedy
issue.body:
### Feature Description

Dear Kiro Team,

I‚Äôm [Antonio Ribeiro](https://github.com/antonioribeiro), a PHP and Laravel OSS engineer whose packages have racked up over 120 million downloads and 14K GitHub stars ([pragmarx.com](https://pragmarx.com)). I build tools for the community, but I don‚Äôt make a dime from them. 

Kiro‚Äôs spec-driven AI IDE is a gem‚Äîuntil I saw your new pricing from August 16, 2025. It‚Äôs like you‚Äôve built a private jet for corporate coders, leaving hobbyists like me hitchhiking on the side of the digital highway. The vibe/spec request split is a wasteful mess, and the costs are so high I‚Äôm eyeing my couch cushions for spare change. Let‚Äôs dive in with some recalculated numbers.

## The Vibe/Spec Split: A Wasteful, Confusing Cash Grab
Splitting requests into ‚ÄúVibe‚Äù (chatty planning, $0.04 each) and ‚ÄúSpec‚Äù (code execution, $0.20 each) is like charging me separately for oxygen and sunlight. Vibe requests are useless because the Vibe agent *constantly* nags me to switch to Spec requests, claiming my chats are ‚Äútoo complex.‚Äù It‚Äôs like being upsold from a $1 coffee to a $20 artisanal latte just to stay awake.

Take my recent attempt at a new feature:
- **Planning**: 3 vibe requests (2 chats) for requirements.
- **Design**: 2 vibe requests (1 chat).
- **Tasks**: 2 vibe requests to create 37 tasks.
- **Execution**: Those 37 tasks would probably burn 111 spec requests‚Äîthat‚Äôs $22 for one feature. For the same price, I could buy an actual computer. The Raspberry Pi Pico 2 is on Amazon right now for ‚Ç¨12.50 ‚Äî dual-core ARM CPU, RAM, USB, GPIO pins, designed in Cambridge, manufactured in silicon fabs, shipped across the world, boxed, delivered to my door‚Ä¶ and it still costs less than creating a single feature for my side project on Kiro.

This split is a resource sink. I barely touch Vibe requests, yet I‚Äôm forced into pricey Spec requests for anything meaningful. Other IDEs don‚Äôt charge for specs‚Äîthey generate them for free in files or chats. Why complicate things with two request types when a single quota would save resources and sanity?

## The Numbers: A Hobbyists‚Äô Budget Apocalypse
For light coding (3-4 hours daily, 30 days/month), I use at least **3,000 spec requests/month**. On full coding days (8-10 hours), I could hit **6,000-10,000 spec requests/month**. Let‚Äôs crunch the numbers:
- **Kiro Pro+ ($40/month)**: 250 spec requests. At 3,000 spec requests/month, this lasts **2-3 days**. For 6,000-10,000 spec requests, it‚Äôs gone in *1-2 days*. Overages for 3,000 requests: 2,750 √ó $0.20 = **$550**. Total: **$590/month**. For 10,000 requests: 9,750 √ó $0.20 = **$1,950**. Total: **$1,990/month**.
- **Kiro Power ($200/month)**: 1,250 spec requests. This covers **12-13 days** at 3,000 requests/month (1,750 remaining √ó $0.20 = **$350**, total: **$550/month**). For 6,000 requests, it lasts **6-7 days** (4,750 remaining √ó $0.20 = **$950**, total: **$1,150/month**). For 10,000 requests, it lasts **4 days** (8,750 remaining √ó $0.20 = **$1,750**, total: **$1,950/month**).
- Compare this to competitors:
  - Amazon Q: $20 for 1,000 requests, $40 for 3,000.
  - Trae: Unlimited requests, slower for free tiers.
  - VS Code + Copilot: 500 free requests for OpenAI 4.1, with spec-like features coming.
  - Cursor: Unlimited usage for $20.
  - Windsurf: $15 for 500 requests, with flexible model choices‚ÄîI can switch to free LLMs like GPT-5 medium, or cheaper ones like Kimi-K2 and Qwen3-coder that cost only 1/2 a request. If I need top-tier power, I select Sonnet 4 and pay 2x credits, letting me control costs based on task complexity. This is what I was using before, and it‚Äôs way more affordable for experimenting.

The $40 Pro+ tier vanishes in 1-3 days, and the $200 Power tier stretches to 4-13 days, depending on my coding intensity. A single spec often eats multiple spec requests, making these quotas feel like a bad joke. For an open-source dev like me, who‚Äôs driven 120M+ downloads for the Laravel community, this pricing is a kick in the shins.

## Why This Hurts (and Wastes Resources)
The vibe/spec split isn‚Äôt just confusing‚Äîit‚Äôs inefficient. Vibe requests go unused because the agent funnels me to Spec requests, wasting my quota on something I don‚Äôt need. Meanwhile, Spec requests are so pricey I‚Äôm rationing them like water in a desert. With AWS‚Äôs infrastructure, you could optimize costs using context diffs or a model router to delegate simple tasks to cheaper LLMs like kimi-k2 or gpt-oss on EC2 instances. As someone who‚Äôs built tools like Laravel Health to monitor server performance, I know you could do better. Instead, you‚Äôre passing the full cost to users, which is baffling for a company with your resources.

This pricing screams ‚Äúenterprise only,‚Äù leaving hobbyists like me‚Äîwho‚Äôve poured years into tools like Google2FA and Countries‚Äîunable to justify $550-$1,990 a month when I‚Äôm not making money. Other tools offer unlimited or high-quota plans for a fraction of the cost, and their spec-like features don‚Äôt come with a separate bill.

## Acknowledging Kiro‚Äôs Strengths‚ÄîBut It‚Äôs Still Too Expensive
I get it‚ÄîKiro‚Äôs model is all about delivering the absolute best coding experience possible, and it‚Äôs truly amazing. The spec-driven approach with Claude Sonnet 4.0 is mind-blowing for complex tasks. But trying to achieve that perfection comes at a cost that‚Äôs just too high for regular users like me who are experimenting without a revenue stream. Tools like Windsurf let me scale costs with task complexity, making it sustainable. Kiro feels like a luxury I can‚Äôt afford, even though I want to.

## A Plea from an Open-Source Dev
Kiro team, I‚Äôm begging you to rethink this before you lose devs like me who love your tool but can‚Äôt afford it. Here‚Äôs how you could win back our broke-but-passionate hearts:
- **Simplify the model**: One request type, one quota. Say, 750 requests for $20.
- **Hobbyist tier**: $5-$10 for 100 vibe/50 spec requests to get us in the door.
- **Lower overages**: $0.20/spec is highway robbery. Try $10/500 requests, expiring in 3 months.
- **Free specs**: Make spec generation free, like other IDEs. It‚Äôs a one-time task, not a recurring cost.
- **Team plans**: Charge enterprises more to subsidize solo coders like me.

I want to keep coding with Kiro, but my wallet‚Äôs screaming louder than the 14K GitHub stars on my repos. Don‚Äôt let this pricing turn your community into a ghost town. Make Kiro a tool for *all* coders, not just those with corporate budgets. As someone who‚Äôs given the community tools like Google2FA and Countries, I know the value of accessibility‚Äîlet‚Äôs bring that to Kiro.

With hope (and a rapidly shrinking bank account),  

Antonio Ribeiro, Your Sad-But-Still-Sassy Open-Source Dev


### Use Case

The coding community‚Äîhobbyists and open-source devs‚Äîtinkers with Kiro for side projects, but the vibe/spec split and sky-high costs make us want to code, not cry!

### Additional Context

_No response_

pkg_install: Ignore version checks on Darwin.

This has now been superceded by CHECK_OS_VERSION, but that will only
exist for users who have installed newer bootstrap kits, so retain this
patch until we're confident most users have updated.

pkg_install: Depend on mksh when bootstrap shell.

This is a belt-and-braces approach just for this macOS binary package
set, it's not wholly suitable for upstreaming as there are corner cases
where it can cause problems (e.g. trying to upgrade a pkg_install tgz
with "pkg_add -DU" when the depending mksh package cannot be found).

mk: Create .pkginfo when calling "package" manually.

This is normally handled by pbulk, however in some cases we want to run
"bmake package" manually, and in those cases we must ensure the pkginfo
file is in sync.

pkgin: Link pkgsrc libraries statically.

There have been enough reports of failed upgrades due to libarchive
going awry to warrant this and simply avoid that failure mode completely.

pkg_install: Disable check_requires().

Still has a number of problems, and the very last thing we want is to be
stuck in a situation that we might not be able to recover from.  The bug
this code was implemented to solve does not really apply to us, and our
users are trained to use pkgin not pkg_add.
lang: Disable gcc14, prefer pkgsrc-extra version.

build, while the -libs include will do the correct things for runtime.
